Adding this in case someone stumbles into this in 2022 and after.

While the answer by [@Predrag Maric][1] was the one that worked for me, there is a missing step in configuring JPA and the SQLite Dialect in most blog posts or tutorials. After spending a day looking into it, I found a solution to this problem. It turns out that the SQL Dialect has an extremely important missing function which is `hasDataTypeInIdentityColumn()` in the class `SQLIdentityColumnSupport`. This is how it looks like after the addition of the function.

```
public class SQLiteIdentityColumnSupport extends IdentityColumnSupportImpl {
    @Override
    public boolean supportsIdentityColumns() {
        return true;
    }

    @Override
    public boolean hasDataTypeInIdentityColumn() {
        return false;
    }

    @Override
    public String getIdentitySelectString(String table, String column, int type) throws MappingException {
        return &quot;select last_insert_rowid()&quot;;
    }

    @Override
    public String getIdentityColumnString(int type) throws MappingException {
        return &quot;integer&quot;;
    }
}
```

Reference of the implementation of the class [can be found here][2].

After that, once one adds `GenerationType.IDENTITY` as the strategy, SQLite will finally work the auto incremented id through and `INSERT` and `UPDATE` operations will work just fine.


  [1]: https://stackoverflow.com/users/4074715/predrag-maric
  [2]: https://github.com/hibernate/hibernate-orm/blob/main/hibernate-community-dialects/src/main/java/org/hibernate/community/dialect/identity/SQLiteIdentityColumnSupport.java

